    </div>
    <div class="aice-report-col">
      <div class="aice-report-col-head">Anthropic — GTG-1002 Disclosure</div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">Executive Summary</span><span class="aice-report-present">PUBLISHED</span></div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">Target Sectors</span><span class="aice-report-present">PUBLISHED</span></div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">Attribution Methodology</span><span class="aice-report-missing">[REDACTED]</span></div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">Indicators of Compromise</span><span class="aice-report-missing">[NOT PUBLISHED]</span></div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">Infrastructure Analysis</span><span class="aice-report-missing">[NOT PUBLISHED]</span></div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">Jailbreak Prompts</span><span class="aice-report-missing">[NOT PUBLISHED]</span></div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">YARA / Detection Rules</span><span class="aice-report-missing">[NOT PUBLISHED]</span></div>
      <div class="aice-report-row"><span class="aice-label">Recommended Mitigations</span><span class="aice-report-present">PUBLISHED</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="aice-report-footer">
      When CrowdStrike, Mandiant, Microsoft, or Google TAG publish nation-state threat reports, they include IOCs so defenders can check their own systems. Anthropic did not.
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>Without IOCs, the approximately thirty targeted organizations cannot determine from Anthropic's report alone whether they were among the victims. Kevin Beaumont, a well-known cybersecurity researcher, wrote that the complete lack of IOCs "strongly suggests they don't want to be called out over that" and said the operational impact of the disclosure "should likely be zero" since existing detections already cover the open-source tooling involved. Daniel Card dismissed the report as "marketing guff." Dan Tentler, cofounder of the Phobos Group, was blunter: "I continue to refuse to believe that attackers are somehow able to get these models to jump through hoops that nobody else can." He also flagged the guardrail asymmetry — why the model apparently cooperated with attackers while, in his words, legitimate users "have to deal with asskissing, stonewalling and acid trips." Bob Rudis, VP of Data Science at GreyNoise Intelligence, called the disclosure a "well-packaged demonstration of trends we've already known about for years" that "doesn't expand the threat model in a meaningful way."</p>

  <p>Toby Murray, professor of cybersecurity at the University of Melbourne, identified the structural problem: defenders cannot determine if they were victimized without IOCs. The report told the world an attack happened. It did not give anyone the tools to verify whether the attack happened to them.</p>

  <p>XBOW, a cybersecurity company specializing in autonomous offensive testing, raised a different question: why would a sophisticated Chinese state-sponsored group use a commercial U.S. AI platform with full activity logging? XBOW suggested that a capable nation-state actor would more plausibly have built or fine-tuned its own in-house model. (XBOW competes in the autonomous offensive testing space, which is relevant to how its analysis is framed.)</p>

  <p>Five months after the disclosure, as of April 2026, no targeted organization has independently and publicly confirmed being breached in the GTG-1002 campaign. All breach claims originate solely from Anthropic.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="incentive">
  <h2><span class="num">03 — The Incentive</span>Who Benefits</h2>
  <p>Yann LeCun, Meta's chief AI scientist, did not hesitate. "You're being played by people who want regulatory capture," he wrote after the disclosure. "They are scaring everyone with dubious studies so that open-source models are regulated out of existence." LeCun has a conflict of interest: Meta competes directly with Anthropic and is the leading corporate advocate for open-source AI models, which Anthropic's safety messaging implicitly constrains.</p>

  <p>David Sacks, then serving as the White House AI advisor, had already accused Anthropic of "running a sophisticated regulatory capture strategy based on fear-mongering" — but that statement came approximately one month before the GTG-1002 disclosure, targeting Anthropic's general safety posture rather than this specific report. After the report was published, Sacks acknowledged the GTG-1002 disclosure was "more on the legitimate side" compared to prior Anthropic safety communications.</p>

  <p>The simultaneous publication is harder to dismiss as coincidence than as strategy. On the same day Anthropic warned the world about an AI-powered espionage campaign exploiting its own model, it published a companion post detailing how it was building AI capabilities for cyber defense. Alarm and sales pitch, side by side. Whether this juxtaposition reflects genuine urgency or calculated positioning, the research bundle cannot resolve.</p>

  <p>A measured center existed. Jim Gumbley, CISO of Thoughtworks, characterized the campaign as a "tooling improvement" rather than a "singularity event," arguing it does not render modern security teams obsolete — but warned that "dismissing the report entirely is a mistake." Christopher Covino of the Institute for AI Policy and Strategy hedged Anthropic's framing to "one of the first" rather than definitively "the first," and noted that the attacks exploited existing security gaps in target organizations rather than defeating robust controls. The AI was fast. The targets were soft.</p>
</section>

<section class="section" id="hearing">
  <h2><span class="num">04 — The Hearing</span>Congress Steps In</h2>
  <p>On November 26, 2025 — thirteen days after the disclosure — House Homeland Security Committee Chair Andrew Garbarino (R-NY), along with Reps. Josh Brecheen (R-OK) and Andy Ogles (R-TN), sent letters to Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei, Google Cloud CEO Thomas Kurian, and Quantum Xchange CEO Eddy Zervigon requesting testimony at a December 17 hearing. The committee's letter described the incident as "consequential for U.S. homeland security because it demonstrates what a capable and well-resourced state-sponsored cyber actor can now accomplish using commercially available U.S. AI systems — even when providers maintain strong safeguards and respond rapidly to signs of misuse."</p>

  <p>The committee was relying on Anthropic's report. It was not independently validating it.</p>

  <p>On December 17, a joint session of House Homeland Security subcommittees heard from four witnesses: Logan Graham from Anthropic's frontier red team, Royal Hansen from Google's security engineering division, Quantum Xchange CEO Eddy Zervigon, and Michael Coates, former Twitter CISO. Congress had requested Dario Amodei. Anthropic sent a red team member. The reason for the substitution has never been publicly explained.</p>

  <p>Graham confirmed under testimony the core claims from Anthropic's report: the 80 to 90 percent autonomy figure, the four to six human decision points, and that the attackers "deceived the model into believing it was conducting ethical cybersecurity testing." He also confirmed that Anthropic's own model code was not compromised and the company itself was not hacked.</p>

